This paper deals with the analysis of optimization algorithms for black-box functions, which is a topic that falls under the scope of several arXiv CS sub-categories. However, given that the paper focuses on the analysis of the unbiased black-box complexity of jump functions, which are a type of combinatorial optimization problem, it is likely that the paper belongs to the cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) sub-category, which deals with optimization algorithms inspired by natural processes such as evolution. Additionally, the paper introduces new tools for the analysis of unbiased black-box complexities, which could also make it relevant to the cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.IT (Information Theory) sub-categories. Finally, the paper presents experimental results that compare the performance of different optimization algorithms on jump functions, which could make it relevant to the cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) and cs.LG (Machine Learning) sub-categories.
